:END:

Magit is decades of interactive-git UX; mine it for what translates to a
non-interactive agent surface. Obvious candidates beyond the fixup/absorb
tasks above: instant fixup (create + fold in one op), branch-scoped log/diff
views shaped for planning (magit-log's --graph equivalent as structured
data), range-diff (compare a branch before/after a rewrite — would pair
perfectly with rehearse), stash/snapshot as a first-class safety net
(magit-stash-worktree ~ our backup refs, but for the worktree), and
worktree-level "discard this hunk" (the destructive sibling of staging by
hunk). Criterion: keep the no-network/no-hooks/no-exec envelope; prefer
verbs that reduce agent round trips.

Survey done [2026-07-14]. Already covered by mime: instant fixup
(git_fixup {worktree/hunks}), autosquash, interactive-rebase verbs
(edit/split/reword/message_edits), blame incl. absorb-target discovery,
recovery ropes (backup ring ≈ magit's reflog reliance, but agent-legible).
Spun out as new tasks: git_absorb (auto-target dirty hunks), git_range_diff
(old-vs-new history after a rewrite, pairs with the backup ring), and
git_discard (drop worktree hunks behind the -worktree parachute ref).
Judged not worth porting: magit's status/log *views* (git_log/git_show
cover the data; rendering is the harness's job), branch/remote management
(network is out of envelope by design), and stash as a first-class store
(warm sessions + the -worktree parachute cover the agent need).


