From docs/agent-feedback.md (agent field notes, 2026-07-14; NOT committed).
~stale_note~ rides the read tools and ~run_program~ (~stale: true~), but
~replace_text~ / ~insert_text~ — the tools an agent is driving when staleness
bites — carry only the ~unsaved~ note. Worst case is the dirty-buffer +
external-change scenario auto-revert deliberately skips: ~replace_text~ then
fails with a bare "no match for the pattern" and no hint that the buffer
diverged from disk. Append the stale note to the edit tools' results AND to
their no-match errors ("the visited file changed on disk and this buffer has
unsaved edits; matching ran against the warm buffer"). The failure moment is
the most-read doc surface the interface has.

Done [2026-07-14]: new =stale_edit_note= (dirty-buffer wording) on
insert_text/replace_text results, both no-match error sites, the edits batch,
and the per-file error of the files form; integration test covers miss +
success + insert_text.


* DONE git_rebase default pick-all doesn't drop commits already in `onto` (patch-id) — duplicates when rebasing a stacked branch onto a rewritten base :git:dogfooding:
:PROPERTIES:
:ARCHIVE_TIME: 2026-07-14 Di 15:36
:ARCHIVE_FILE: /vagrant/mime-rs/todo.org
:ARCHIVE_OLPATH: MCP / agent UX
:ARCHIVE_CATEGORY: todo
:ARCHIVE_TODO: DONE
:END:
:LOGBOOK:
- State "DONE"       from "TODO"       [2026-07-07 Di 10:24]
- State "TODO"       from              [2026-07-07 Di 08:31]
:END:

From driving mime to rebase a stacked branch (2026-07-07): branch B sits on base A; A's top commits were REORDERED (rewritten to new oids, identical patch-ids). Re-rebasing B onto the rewritten A via ~git_rebase {onto: A}~ with the DEFAULT (plan-less) pick-all replayed A's rewritten commits a second time — B ended up with duplicate commits — because the merge-base with the rewritten A had moved BELOW the rewrite, so ~onto..HEAD~ still contained B's old copies of those commits and pick-all replayed every one verbatim.

Stock ~git rebase~ drops commits already present upstream by patch-id (cherry-pick / already-applied detection — the ~--no-reapply-cherry-picks~ default), so the same "reorder the base, then rebase the stack" sequence yields NO duplicates. mime's default pick-all has no such detection, so the natural stacked-branch workflow silently duplicates; recovering needs an explicit plan with a ~drop~ on each rewritten commit (what I did to fix it).

Fix: on the plan-less rebase, omit commits in ~onto..HEAD~ whose patch-id already exists in ~onto~ (match git's cherry-pick detection), or at minimum WARN and report them so the duplication isn't silent. Consider a ~reapply_cherry_picks~ flag for the rare keep-them case. rehearse already lists the resulting commits — flagging the would-be duplicates there would catch it pre-apply too.

Done [2026-07-07] on branch ~rebase-drop-cherry-picks~: the plan-less pick-all now drops commits already present in ~onto~ by patch-id (matches git's ~--no-reapply-cherry-picks~ default) and REPORTS the skipped commits so it's never silent; a ~reapply_cherry_picks~ flag overrides. An explicit ~plan~/~autosquash~ is unaffected. Cross-checked the drop set against real ~git rebase~.


* DONE git_rebase rehearse preview doesn't fold fixup/squash steps :bug:git_rebase:
:PROPERTIES:
:ARCHIVE_TIME: 2026-07-14 Di 15:36
:ARCHIVE_FILE: /vagrant/mime-rs/todo.org
:ARCHIVE_OLPATH: MCP / agent UX
:ARCHIVE_CATEGORY: todo
:ARCHIVE_TODO: DONE
:END:
:LOGBOOK:
- State "DONE"       from "TODO"       [2026-07-02 Do 16:01]
- State "TODO"       from              [2026-07-01 Mi 13:51]
:END:

In ~git_rebase~ with ~rehearse: true~, ~fixup~/~squash~ plan steps are not folded
in the preview: the rehearsal lists one commit line per plan step (each
~fixup~/~squash~ step shown as a separate commit carrying the melded message) and
its "-> N commit(s)" summary reports the unfolded step count.

A real (non-rehearse) apply of the identical plan folds correctly — verified on
an 8-commit branch: a [~reword~, ~fixup~] pair produced 7 commits with a
byte-identical tree.

The misleading preview makes it look like ~fixup~/~squash~ won't fold, which
nearly caused abandoning a valid mime fold in favour of a manual
~git reset --soft~.

Fix: ~rehearse~ should simulate the fold so the previewed commit list and count
match what apply produces.

DONE (2026-07): rehearse now replaces the superseded entry for a squash/fixup step
(the fold re-parents onto the previous commit's parent), so the previewed commit
list and "-> N commits" count match a real apply. Test asserts preview==apply.


* DONE git_rebase: autosquash/absorb — fold a change into the commit that owns it :git:dogfooding:
:PROPERTIES:
:ARCHIVE_TIME: 2026-07-14 Di 15:36
:ARCHIVE_FILE: /vagrant/mime-rs/todo.org
:ARCHIVE_OLPATH: MCP / agent UX
:ARCHIVE_CATEGORY: todo
:ARCHIVE_TODO: DONE
:END:
:LOGBOOK:
- State "DONE"       from "TODO"       [2026-07-02 Do 15:58]
- State "TODO"       from              [2026-06-30 Di 12:13]
:END:

From driving mime to rewrite this repo's own history (2026-06): the common
task "I just made this change — fold it into the commit it belongs to" has no
one-call path. Each fold took (a) a raw ~git add~ + ~git commit~ to make a temp
fixup (mime has no stage/commit primitive — correctly, since its git ops run no
hooks, so commit CREATION should stay on raw ~git -s~ to fire the sign-off
commit-msg hook), then (b) a ~git_rebase~ with the ENTIRE plan hand-authored:
every commit oid from the target onward listed in order with the fixup slotted
in. Step (b) is the friction — transcribing untouched ~pick~ steps just to say
"fixup A into B"; on a long branch it is tedious and easy to drop or reorder a
commit. ~rehearse~ (tree-IDENTICAL check) makes it safe, not quick.

Two improvements, smallest first:

1. *Autosquash-style SPARSE plans for ~git_rebase~.* Let the plan express only
   the RELATIONSHIP and auto-pick the rest of ~onto..HEAD~ in order — e.g.
   ~plan: [{action: fixup, commit: X, into: Y}]~ moves X to sit under Y as a
   fixup and picks every other commit unchanged. This is git's
   ~--autosquash~ semantics as data (no ~fixup!~-subject magic needed). Removes
   the enumerate-untouched-commits chore with no new tool.

2. *A ~git_fixup~ / absorb tool.* One rehearsable call taking a target commit +
   a source — a commit, OR the staged/worktree changes directly — that does the
   temp-commit → move-under-target → fixup dance internally and lands the
   amended history. A mime-created temp commit is fine here even though mime
   runs no hooks: ~fixup~ DISCARDS the temp message and PRESERVES the target's
   existing (already-signed) message, so no sign-off is dropped. Stretch: a
   ~git absorb~-style AUTO-TARGET that maps each worktree hunk to the commit
   that last touched those lines — i.e. the find-the-commit half tracked under
   the blame-shaped read item — so "I edited line X, tuck it into whatever
   commit introduced X" becomes one call.

Relation to existing items: the blame-shaped "which commit owns this?" read is
the DISCOVERY half (find the target); this is the ACTION half (fold into it).
The split/move item is the inverse — repartition what is ALREADY committed.
Together they are one vocabulary: find-the-commit → fold-in / split-out.

DONE (2026-07): both fold paths shipped.
- ~git_rebase~ ~autosquash = [{commit, into, action?}]~: sparse plan that relocates
  only the named commits (fixup/squash under their target) and auto-picks the rest
  of onto..HEAD — the enumerate-untouched-commits chore is gone.
- ~git_fixup {target, source}~: one-call fold of a COMMITTED source into target
  (target keeps its signed message); infers the base, reuses the sequencer.
Intentionally NOT done: worktree/staged AUTO-absorb (commit-from-worktree). Commit
creation stays on raw ~git -s~ to fire the sign-off hook, per the driver design; a
committed source covers the fold. The ~git absorb~ auto-target (hunk -> owning
commit) still belongs with the blame-the-hunk half of [[git-blame]].


* DONE save_buffer {to:} copy-out can clobber another live session's visited file [#C] :mcp:
:PROPERTIES:
:ARCHIVE_TIME: 2026-07-14 Di 15:36
:ARCHIVE_FILE: /vagrant/mime-rs/todo.org
:ARCHIVE_OLPATH: MCP / agent UX
:ARCHIVE_CATEGORY: todo
:ARCHIVE_TODO: DONE
:END:
:LOGBOOK:
- State "DONE"       from "TODO"       [2026-07-03 Fr 11:31]
:END:

From the mcp-surface-review code review (2026-06-24). ~Workspace::write_copy_to~
writes a different path with no stale guard and no cross-session awareness, so
~save_buffer {path: A, to: B}~ where B is the visited file of ANOTHER warm
session with unsaved edits silently overwrites B — and B's own stale guard never
fires (the change happened out from under it). Pre-existing in spirit (the old
~save_to~ also skipped the guard for a non-visited path), but the explicit
copy branch is now the documented route. Low severity (localhost, single-user,
cp-like intent), but worth a guard: before the copy, check whether ~to~ is
canonically some other live session's visited path and refuse / warn.

DONE (2026-07): save_buffer's copy-out branch now refuses when the target is
canonically the visited file of a DIFFERENT live session with unsaved edits
(clobbers_unsaved_session), naming it. A clean session or an unrelated path is
fine. Unit test covers the dirty-collision, clean, own-session, and no-collision
cases.


* DONE Discoverability: structural + conflict-resolution verbs hidden in ~run_program~ [#C]
:PROPERTIES:
:ARCHIVE_TIME: 2026-07-14 Di 15:36
:ARCHIVE_FILE: /vagrant/mime-rs/todo.org
:ARCHIVE_OLPATH: MCP / agent UX/MCP command-surface review — prune the middle, grow power via params
:ARCHIVE_CATEGORY: todo
:ARCHIVE_TODO: DONE
:ARCHIVE_ITAGS: mcp
:END:
Structural editing (treesit nodes/queries) is surfaced only as ~outline~; the
conflict RESOLUTION verbs (~conflict-keep~ etc.) are ~run_program~ functions,
not tools (the ~conflicts~ tool only reports). ~help {treesit|conflicts}~
bridges both, but it is a discovery step. Decide whether that is the intended
"small surface, deep engine" tradeoff (then document it as such) or worth one
more surfaced affordance.

DONE: chose to keep the small surface and make the tradeoff explicit — the
~instructions~ now say the deep vocabulary (regex / treesit / conflict-keep …)
lives inside ~run_program~ by design, reached via help {topic|tool}.


