Non-blocking code-quality items from the 2026-06-29 pre-PR review of the
edit / message_edits / split work — no correctness impact:
- The =if step.action == Action::Split { land_split } else { land_step }=
  dispatch is duplicated verbatim in =drive= and =continue_op=; fold into one
  =land()= helper so a future special-landing action (or a land_* signature
  change) is edited once, not in two places that can drift.
- =changed_paths= extracts diff paths via =diff.foreach= (four closure args)
  while =show= already does the same =new_file()/old_file()= pick over the
  simpler =diff.deltas()= iterator — share one helper.
- =split_assignment= does =touched.iter().any(...)= per assigned path (O(n*m))
  though =touched= is sorted+deduped and =assigned= is already a HashSet; use a
  =HashSet= (or =binary_search=) for symmetric O(1) membership.
- =split_commits= re-runs =changed_paths= + =split_assignment= that =begin=
  already validated, and calls =repo.find_commit(current)= twice per part
  (prev_tree + parent) — fetch the commit once and reuse.
- =message_edits= / =split_into= are parsed in three hand-rolled forms with
  divergent keys: =plan_arg= reads {find, replace, append} / {message, paths,
  into}; =save_state= writes {find, with} / {…, rest}; =load_state= reads them
  back. The persisted-vs-input key mismatch (=replace= vs =with=, absent-paths
  vs =rest=) is easy to break silently — unify, ideally via serde derives on
  the structs.

DONE (2026-07): all five items addressed. land() helper folds the dispatch;
changed_paths/show share delta_path; split_assignment uses a HashSet;
split_commits fetches the current commit once. The message-edit persist keys now
match the MCP input ({find, replace, append}, was {find, with}) — a state
round-trip test guards the drift the review flagged. Went with matching keys
rather than a full serde-derive migration: rewriting working, tested persistence
for a cosmetic gain wasn't worth the risk, and the round-trip test covers it.


* DONE Inspect the need for a git-blame-shaped "which commit owns this?" read :git:dogfooding:
:PROPERTIES:
:ARCHIVE_TIME: 2026-07-14 Di 15:36
:ARCHIVE_FILE: /vagrant/mime-rs/todo.org
:ARCHIVE_OLPATH: MCP / agent UX
:ARCHIVE_CATEGORY: todo
:ARCHIVE_TODO: DONE
:END:
:LOGBOOK:
- State "DONE"       from "TODO"       [2026-07-02 Do 16:14]
:END:

The edit / squash / fixup / split work all assume the agent ALREADY knows
which commit to target. But the common real task is the reverse: the agent has
an uncommitted change (a hunk in the worktree, or lines it just edited) and
needs to find the commit it logically belongs to — to fold it in via an =edit=
amend, a =fixup=, or a =move= into the right commit. Without a blame-shaped
read it falls back to shelling out to =git blame= / =git log -L=.

Investigate (NOT yet committed to building): a read-only =git_blame {repo, path,
lines?}=-style tool reporting, per line (or per worktree-hunk), the last commit
that touched it — oid + summary, ideally scoped to the current op's range so the
answer is "which of MY commits owns this", not "any commit in history". Output
should compose into the other git tools: the reported oid feeds =git_rebase=
plan {commit, action: fixup|edit} or a =move= directive directly, so
find-the-commit → fold-in is one vocabulary.

Open questions to settle first: (1) is per-line blame the right granularity, or
blame-the-hunk (map a worktree diff hunk → the commit that last touched those
lines)? (2) confine to onto..HEAD by default? (3) does git2 expose
=Repository::blame_file= with the options we need, and is it fast enough on big
files (it re-walks history)? (4) is this even needed once =edit= lands, or do
agents naturally drive it via git_log + git_show? Measure on real sessions
before building.

DONE (2026-07): shipped a read-only ~git_blame~ MCP tool — ~git_blame {repo, path,
lines?}~. Per-line "which commit last touched this", collapsed into contiguous
same-commit hunks (oid + summary); optional ~[start, end]~ line window; accepts an
absolute path (what grep/occur return) or a workdir-relative one. Built on git2's
~blame_file~ — the find-the-commit half that feeds a ~git_rebase~ plan {commit,
action: fixup|edit}. Landed with a sequencer test + doc/help/schema wiring.

Remaining: (1) history-scope — confine the blame to ~onto..HEAD~ by default so the
answer is "which of MY commits owns this", not any commit in history
(~BlameOptions~ newest/oldest); (2) blame-the-hunk — map a worktree diff hunk (not
just a line span) to the commit that last touched those lines, so an uncommitted
change routes straight into a ~fixup~/~move~.

DONE (2026-07): the two remaining enhancements shipped.
- ~since~ param scopes blame to ~since..~ (oldest_commit boundary) — "which of MY
  commits owns this line".
- ~worktree: true~ maps each UNCOMMITTED hunk to the commit that last set the lines
  it touches (git-absorb-style target discovery); each oid feeds git_fixup/git_move.
This closes the find-the-commit -> fold-in vocabulary end to end.


* DONE git_rebase: split a commit + move changes between commits :git:dogfooding:
:PROPERTIES:
:ARCHIVE_TIME: 2026-07-14 Di 15:36
:ARCHIVE_FILE: /vagrant/mime-rs/todo.org
:ARCHIVE_OLPATH: MCP / agent UX
:ARCHIVE_CATEGORY: todo
:ARCHIVE_TODO: DONE
:END:
:LOGBOOK:
- State "DONE"       from "TODO"       [2026-07-02 Do 15:47]
:END:

The plan reorders / squashes / drops WHOLE commits, and the planned =edit=
action (above) amends one commit's tree in place — but nothing REPARTITIONS
what is already committed:
- split one commit into two or more along path or hunk boundaries (e.g. code
  in one commit, docs/notes in another);
- move a file or hunk OUT of one commit and INTO an adjacent one.
(Reordering whole commits is already covered by plan order.)

Without these, an agent asked to "put these changes in a different commit"
must abandon the in-process sequencer and hand-drive =git reset --soft= +
selective =git add= + recommit — error-prone (easy to mis-stage and silently
change the resulting tree) and exactly the transactional, rehearsable job mime
is built for.

Shape: extend the plan with a =split= action ({commit, into: [{message, paths
| hunks}, …]}) and/or a =move= directive ({from, to, paths | hunks}), reusing
the path / hunk selection the engine already has (treesit nodes, occur / grep
hunks). Offer a =rehearse= of the resulting history — the tree-diff of each new
commit — so a mis-partition is caught before it is written, not after.

DONE so far (branch =sequencer-tree-edits=): PATH-based =split=. The =split= action
takes =into = [{message, paths}]=; it partitions a commit's changes by file path
into N commits (one part may omit =paths= as the catch-all), pre-validated in
=begin= against the commit's own diff so a bad partition fails before mutation, and
=rehearse=-able. Trees are built in-memory, never touching the worktree.
Remaining: HUNK-level split (partial-hunk application, =git add -p=-grade) and the
=move= directive (relocate changes between existing adjacent commits).

DONE (2026-07): both halves shipped.
- HUNK-level split: a split part now takes ~hunks = [{path, lines:[a,b]}]~ (new-side
  spans, the numbers grep/blame return) alongside/instead of ~paths~; splits that
  name hunks route through an ~apply_to_tree~ builder that reassembles the exact
  original tree in the final part. Path-only splits keep the old blob-copy builder.
- MOVE: new ~git_move {from, to, paths?, hunks?}~ relocates a change between two
  ADJACENT commits (must be in ~from~, not ~to~) and replays the tail via the
  sequencer. Invariant: the branch's final tree is unchanged — only the split point
  moves. Both validated at begin time, before mutation; tests + docs + help + schema.


* DONE git_rebase: let `reword`/`squash` take a message edit, not the whole message :git:
:PROPERTIES:
:ARCHIVE_TIME: 2026-07-14 Di 15:36
