DONE (2026-06, commit ~4d16fd8~): ~src/regex_dialect.rs~ is an Emacs→RE2
syntax translator at the ~cached_regex~ compile chokepoint — it maps ~\|~
alternation, ~\(...\)~ groups, ~\{n,m\}~, ~\(?:...\)~ shy groups and the
~\`~ / ~\'~ anchors, treats bare ~( | {~ as literals, and errors clearly on
constructs RE2 can't express (backreferences, ~\=~, ~\_<~ / ~\_>~, ~\s~ / ~\S~
classes). ~regexp-quote~ / occur's literal-quoting now emit Emacs-style
escaping so quoted text isn't re-read as group syntax. The original "no
match" on ~\|~ alternation + escaped metachars is fixed; the supported
dialect is documented in help{regex}.

Original report follows.

From an agent session (2026-06-11) driving git-conflict resolution
and TOML/Rust edits via MCP: ~replace_text~ patterns
with RE2-style escapes (~\[features\]~) and ~occur~ with ~|~
alternation returned "no match" where the literal text (and ~search~
exact mode) matched fine — occur even echoed the translated emacs
regex ~features\|dependencies~ yet found nothing. Agents fall back to
literal patterns, losing regex entirely. Reproduce, fix the RE2→emacs
translation (or document the supported dialect precisely), and add
round-trip tests for escaped metachars + alternation.


* DONE save_buffer {to:} rebinds the visited file — a footgun for path-keyed sessions [#B] :dogfooding:
:PROPERTIES:
:ARCHIVE_TIME: 2026-07-14 Di 15:36
:ARCHIVE_FILE: /vagrant/mime-rs/todo.org
:ARCHIVE_OLPATH: MCP / agent UX
:ARCHIVE_CATEGORY: todo
:ARCHIVE_TODO: DONE
:END:
DONE (2026-06-24, branch ~mcp-surface-review~): implemented exactly the fix
below — ~to:~ to a different file is a pure copy-out (~Workspace::write_copy_to~,
no rebind, visited file + baseline untouched); same-path ~to:~ stays an in-place
save. See the surface-review item that subsumed this.


Hit during the 2026-06-11 switchyard session. Recovery sequence after a
bad save: ~save_buffer {path: X, to: TMP}~ to park the good buffer, then
~mv TMP X~ — but the save-as had REBOUND the session's visited file to
TMP, so the next ~save: true~ on the same session hit TMP's stale-guard
("deleted on disk") instead of writing X, and the fix was a second
save-as back onto X itself.

Emacs' ~write-file~ does rebind, but mime's sessions are KEYED by
canonical path — a session opened as X that silently starts visiting TMP
breaks the addressing contract (the warm session is still listed under
X, yet saves target TMP). For an agent, save-as is almost always "export
a copy", not "move my session".

Fix: make ~to:~ a pure copy-out (write the bytes, leave the visited file
and stale-guard baseline untouched). If a true rename-the-session
operation is ever wanted, make it explicit (~rebind: true~ or a separate
tool). Also worth a line in ~help {topic: "sessions"}~ either way.


