DONE (2026-06, commits ~a3379ef~ + ~85ddf0e~ hardening): a read-only ~grep
{pattern, files | glob, mode, nlines}~ tool landed with occur's output shape,
per-file headers and a hit cap, sandbox-confined to ~$MIME_ROOTS~; its file
list feeds ~replace_text {files: …}~ as planned.

The biggest reason the agent still shells out to =grep -rn= / =sed -n=
mid-edit: =occur= is per-buffer, so "which files mention X" and "show
me that region in three files" have no MCP answer — every multi-file
question drops to Bash, then comes BACK to mime for the edit. The
sandbox already confines paths to =$MIME_ROOTS=, so a read-only
=grep {pattern, files | glob, mode, nlines}= tool (occur's output
shape, one header per file, hit cap) fits the tier. Bonus: its file
list feeds =replace_text {files: …}= directly — search and cross-file
edit would share one vocabulary. A =read_region {path, start_line,
end_line}= alias for "lines 120–140 of X" already exists; the gap is
purely the multi-file fan-out.

